A traditional Cantonese restaurant that's been a stalwart in Chinatown for decades. It's got the ambiance of old Chinatown but has clearly evolved with the times to broaden it's appeal to a greater number of people. That being said, it's definitely got the old school vibes. You need to grab the staffs attention to get what you want. The menu is very authentic and very much old-school traditional Cantonese. No worries about language barriers here. Pricing is very competitive and the quality of the food is good. The Cantonese chicken came out fresh from the fryer. If you haven't had Chinese fried chicken, this place does it well.

So I like this place. It's every much a place that you would take family or like your grandma. It looks like a proper restaurant from a slightly older time, where people just came to eat. Service was good but the wait staff lack some social skills but I chalk it up to the cultural gap. No one even noticed me when I walked in, I had to ask how long for a table, and I was told to follow someone to my table who wasn't really showing me the way.  All that said, the food was good! I had the lamb with cumin and I think I'll have dreams about that for a long long time. I also had the Singapore noodles which were really well made, both portions were large but I could eat that lamb for the rest of forever. They also have free dessert which you should ask for, I asked for the dessert menu, they said they had none but we're serving 'pudding' and I asked the cost and they said free. The pudding was more like a sweet soup made of kidney beans and tapioca and is served hot. I ate the whole thing it was super delicious.  Also the service was really quick given that the restaurant was almost totally full. Huge tables too, you could come with a party of 8-10 people

We have ordered from here several times for carryout with good experiences; however, we have been disappointed the last two times. The soft shell crab has been consistent (and has been excellent the past two times, as always) but the chow meins we have ordered are devoid of flavor. Last month, it was iffy (not a lot of flavor, though manageable) but today confirmed it: literally veggies and seafood laid on top of the noodles (maybe oil mixed in?). Nothing else. I don't know if the menu changed and we are missing something, but from past experience we are used to having seasoning of some type (soy sauce, or something). This reminded me of buttered noodles. It's really unfortunate, but seems like a consistency issue. If we ever order from here again it will solely be for the soft shell crab which, again, has remained consistent.

I would say the rice clay pot dishes and lobsters are the main attraction. I came here for chow fun and egg rolls and 3 things were disappointing. I ordered through yelp and got carryout.  The egg rolls were a little small but were slightly crispy outside due to the thinner wonton wraps. They were not peanut butter egg rolls but even without that they were bland and almost creamy? I would never get those again.  I also got beef with chinese broccoli chow fun. I LOVE CHOW FUN!!! & pad sie (see) ew... but this was not very good. The sauce was good but VERY watered down in taste and consistency. The noodles were good, nice and thick and just chewy. They could (i think should) have been a little charred for flavor and slightly crispy noodle skin. But everything was cooked well but i feel the dish lacked that "char" flavor.  Lastly I got hot oil on the side for my chow fun.  It was just horrible. "Hot oil" by definition should be HOT. Ir was not, even all the pepper flake paste was bland and the oil had a strange taste I don't know how to describe.  Although I will probably never be coming here again because of their 1 star egg rolls and 2 star chow fun I am very grateful for their fantastic service. Very friendly and got everything spot on, thank you.
